        <h1>SAE Question Bank 2076 - 2076</h1>
        <p><strong>Full Marks:</strong> 60 + 20 + 20</p>
        <p><strong>Pass Marks:</strong> 24 + 8 + 8</p>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 hours</p>
    <h2>Section A: Attempts any TWO Questions</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>What is intellectual property? How do you protect such property using copyright, patient, and trade secret? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Intellectual property refers to the creations of the mind, such as inventions, literary and artistic works, symbols, names, and designs, that are protected by law. There are three main types of intellectual property protection: copyright, patent, and trade secret.</p>
<p>Copyright is a legal protection for original works of authorship, such as books, music, and software. Copyright protection gives the owner exclusive rights to control the use of the work, including the right to reproduce, distribute, and display the work. Copyright protection is automatic upon creation of the work and lasts for the life of the creator plus a certain number of years after their death. To protect their copyright, owners can use copyright notices and register their work with the government.</p>
<p>A patent is a legal protection for inventions, such as machines, processes, and products. Patents give the owner exclusive rights to use and sell the invention for a certain number of years. To obtain a patent, the invention must be novel, non-obvious, and useful, and the owner must file a patent application with the government. Patent protection lasts for a set period of time, typically 20 years from the date of filing.</p>
<p>A trade secret is a type of intellectual property protection for confidential information that provides a competitive advantage to a business, such as customer lists, formulas, and processes. Trade secret protection is not automatic and requires the owner to take reasonable steps to keep the information confidential. To protect their trade secrets, owners can use non-disclosure agreements, limit access to the information, and use other security measures to prevent unauthorized disclosure.</p>
<p>In order to protect their intellectual property, owners must take active steps to enforce their rights. This may include monitoring for infringement, sending cease and desist letters, and filing lawsuits to stop infringement and seek damages. It is also important for owners to educate themselves on their rights and options for protecting their intellectual property.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Define ethics and ethical theory. What are the different ethical theories? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Ethics refers to the branch of philosophy that deals with moral principles and values, including concepts such as right and wrong, good and bad, and justice and fairness. It is concerned with determining what actions and behaviors are acceptable and desirable, and what ones are not.</p>
<p>Ethical theory refers to the various frameworks and systems that have been developed to guide ethical decision-making. These theories provide a foundation for understanding and evaluating ethical issues, and can help individuals and organizations make more informed and consistent ethical choices.</p>
<p>There are several major ethical theories, including:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Utilitarianism:</strong></span></p>
<p>This theory holds that the morality of an action should be judged by its overall consequences or utility and that the best action is the one that maximizes overall happiness or pleasure and minimizes overall pain or suffering.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Deontology:</strong></span></p>
<p>This theory emphasizes the inherent rightness or wrongness of actions, regardless of their consequences. Deontological ethical systems emphasize rules and duties and hold that certain actions are always morally required, regardless of their outcomes.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Virtue ethics:</strong></span></p>
<p>This theory focuses on developing good character traits or virtues, such as honesty, courage, and compassion. Virtue ethics emphasizes the importance of cultivating these virtues in individuals, and holds that the moral quality of actions is determined by the character of the person performing them.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Ethics of care:</strong></span></p>
<p>This theory emphasizes the importance of relationships and caring for others, particularly in situations where vulnerability and dependence are involved. The ethics of care holds that moral decision-making should be guided by compassion and empathy and that relationships and context play a key role in determining what is right and wrong.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Ethical relativism:</strong></span></p>
<p>This theory holds that moral principles and values are relative to individual or cultural perspectives and that there is no objective standard of right and wrong. Ethical relativism emphasizes the importance of respecting different cultural values and norms, but can also lead to moral relativism, in which all actions and values are seen as equally valid.</p>
<p>Each of these ethical theories has its own strengths and weaknesses, and different individuals and organizations may find one or more of them more compelling or relevant depending on their particular circumstances and values.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What is the digital divide? Explain different enablers of the digital divide.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The digital divide refers to the gap between those who have access to digital technologies and those who do not. This gap can be related to differences in income, education, geographic location, and other factors that affect individuals&#8217; ability to access and use digital technologies. The digital divide can have significant implications for individuals and communities, including disparities in access to information, education, employment opportunities, and social and political engagement.</p>
<p>There are several factors that can contribute to the digital divide, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Infrastructure:</strong> The availability of broadband internet and other digital infrastructure can vary widely depending on geographic location, with rural and remote areas often having less access than urban areas.</li>
<li><strong>Cost:</strong> The cost of digital technologies, including devices and internet access, can be a barrier for individuals and families with limited financial resources.</li>
<li><strong>Skills and education:</strong> Individuals who lack digital skills or have limited education may struggle to effectively use digital technologies.</li>
<li><strong>Age:</strong> Older adults may be less likely to use digital technologies, which can contribute to a generational divide in digital access and use.</li>
<li><strong>Language and cultural barriers:</strong> Individuals who speak languages other than the dominant language of a particular country or who come from different cultural backgrounds may face barriers to digital access and use.</li>
<li><strong>Disability:</strong> Individuals with disabilities may face barriers to digital access and use if technologies are not designed to be accessible.</li>
<li><strong>Government policies:</strong> Government policies related to digital infrastructure, education, and access can either enable or exacerbate the digital divide.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, the digital divide is a complex issue with many different contributing factors. Addressing the digital divide requires a multifaceted approach that involves addressing infrastructure, cost, education, and other barriers to digital access and use.</p>
</div>
<h2>Section B: Attempts any EIGHT Questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>What are different application of sociology?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Sociology is a broad field that has a wide range of applications in various areas of society. Some of the different applications of sociology include:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Education:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociology is used to study the education system and its impact on individuals and society. Sociologists study topics such as educational inequality, the role of education in social mobility, and the impact of education on socialization and identity.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Health:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociologists study the social factors that influence health and healthcare, including healthcare access and inequalities, health behaviors, and the social determinants of health.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Criminal justice:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociology is used to study crime, the criminal justice system, and the social factors that contribute to crime and criminal behavior. Sociologists study topics such as the impact of social inequality on crime rates, the role of race and ethnicity in the criminal justice system, and the effectiveness of different types of criminal justice interventions.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Politics:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociology is used to study political systems, political institutions, and political behavior. Sociologists study topics such as political participation, political socialization, and the impact of political systems on social inequality.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Social welfare:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociologists study the social welfare system and its impact on individuals and society. Sociologists study topics such as poverty, social inequality, and the effectiveness of different types of social welfare policies and interventions.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>f) Family and gender:</strong></span></p>
<p>Sociology is used to study the family, gender roles, and social factors that influence family structures and relationships. Sociologists study topics such as the impact of social inequality on family structures, the role of gender in family dynamics, and the impact of family structures on individuals and society.</p>
<p>Overall, sociology has a wide range of applications and is used to study various aspects of society and social interactions. Sociologists use a variety of research methods to study these topics, including surveys, interviews, observations, and experiments.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the merits of computer ethics in education?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Computer ethics is an important topic to teach in education, especially in the context of technology and digital literacy. Here are some of the merits of teaching computer ethics in education:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Promotes responsible and ethical use of technology:</strong></span></p>
<p>By teaching computer ethics, students can learn about the ethical and social implications of technology use, and develop responsible and ethical habits in their use of technology.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Builds critical thinking skills:</strong></span></p>
<p>Computer ethics education can help students develop critical thinking skills by exploring ethical dilemmas related to technology use, and considering the different perspectives and solutions to these dilemmas.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Enhances digital citizenship:</strong></span></p>
<p>Computer ethics education can help students become informed and responsible digital citizens, who are aware of their rights and responsibilities in the online world.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Increases awareness of cyber security:</strong></span></p>
<p>Computer ethics education can also help students understand the importance of cyber security and privacy, and how to protect themselves and others online.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Prepares students for the future workforce:</strong></span></p>
<p>In a world where technology is constantly advancing, computer ethics education can help prepare students for careers in technology, by instilling in them the values and ethical principles that are critical for success in the technology industry.</p>
<p>Overall, computer ethics education can help students become well-rounded individuals who are equipped with the knowledge and skills to use technology responsibly, ethically, and effectively in their personal and professional lives.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Has the internet made software protection easier or more difficulty? Why or Why not?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The internet has made software protection both easier and more difficult in different ways.</p>
<p>On the one hand, the internet has made it easier for software companies to protect their software through the use of digital rights management (DRM) technologies. These technologies can help prevent unauthorized copying, sharing, and distribution of software by encrypting software files and requiring users to have a valid license key to access the software. Additionally, the internet has made it easier for software companies to track and monitor the use of their software, and to detect and respond to instances of piracy or unauthorized use.</p>
<p>On the other hand, the internet has also made it more difficult for software companies to protect their software, as the widespread availability of the internet has made it easier for pirates and hackers to distribute and share unauthorized copies of software. Additionally, the internet has made it easier for users to access and download pirated or unauthorized versions of software, and to circumvent DRM technologies through the use of hacking tools and techniques.</p>
<p>Overall, the internet has both facilitated and complicated software protection efforts, and has created a complex and dynamic landscape for software companies to navigate as they seek to protect their intellectual property and prevent unauthorized use and distribution of their software.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What is electronic employee monitoring? What are the consequences of electronic monitoring?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Electronic employee monitoring refers to the use of electronic tools and technologies to track and monitor employees&#8217; activities in the workplace. This may include the use of computer software to monitor employees&#8217; internet and email use, video cameras to monitor employees&#8217; movements, or GPS tracking to monitor employees&#8217; location and movements.</p>
<p>The consequences of electronic monitoring can vary depending on the specific context and the way in which monitoring is implemented. Here are some potential consequences:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Invasion of privacy:</strong></span></p>
<p>Electronic monitoring can be perceived as an invasion of privacy by employees, especially if they are not aware of the specific monitoring activities or if the monitoring is perceived as excessive.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Decreased trust and morale:</strong></span></p>
<p>Electronic monitoring can erode trust between employees and employers, as employees may feel that they are not trusted to perform their jobs without constant monitoring. This can also lead to decreased morale and job satisfaction.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Increased stress and anxiety:</strong></span></p>
<p>Knowing that they are being monitored can increase employees&#8217; stress and anxiety levels, which can negatively impact their performance and well-being.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Legal and ethical concerns:</strong></span></p>
<p>Employers must ensure that their electronic monitoring activities comply with legal and ethical standards, such as protecting employees&#8217; privacy rights and avoiding discrimination based on personal characteristics or activities.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Positive outcomes:</strong></span></p>
<p>Electronic monitoring can also have positive outcomes, such as increased productivity, improved safety, and better compliance with company policies and procedures.</p>
<p>Overall, electronic monitoring can have both positive and negative consequences, and it is important for employers to carefully consider the potential benefits and risks before implementing electronic monitoring in the workplace.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the causes of software failure?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>There are many possible causes of software failure, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Programming errors: These can include coding mistakes, logic errors, and syntax errors that cause the software to behave in unexpected or incorrect ways.</li>
<li>Integration issues: If the software needs to work with other systems or components, issues can arise if these other systems are not compatible or if there are communication problems.</li>
<li>Data issues: Problems with data, such as incorrect or incomplete data or data corruption, can cause the software to behave incorrectly or fail altogether.</li>
<li>Hardware or infrastructure problems: The software may fail if the hardware it runs on is not reliable or if the infrastructure it depends on is not properly configured or maintained.</li>
<li>Security vulnerabilities: Software may fail if it is vulnerable to security threats such as hacking or malware.</li>
<li>User error: If the software is difficult to use or if users are not properly trained, they may make mistakes that cause the software to fail.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, software failure can be caused by a wide range of factors, and it is important for software developers and testers to be aware of these potential causes and to take steps to prevent or mitigate them.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is software risk? How do you assess and manage software risk?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Software risk refers to the potential for negative impacts or consequences associated with software development, deployment, and maintenance. These risks can arise from a wide range of factors, including technical complexity, changes in business requirements, human error, security vulnerabilities, and external factors such as changes in regulations or market conditions.</p>
<p>Assessing and managing software risk is an important part of the software development process, and involves several steps:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Identification of risks:</strong></span></p>
<p>The first step in managing software risk is to identify potential risks associated with the software development and deployment process. This can be done through techniques such as risk analysis, brainstorming, and reviewing past experiences and lessons learned.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Prioritization of risks:</strong></span></p>
<p>Once potential risks have been identified, they need to be prioritized based on their potential impact and likelihood of occurrence. This can help focus risk management efforts on the most critical risks.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Mitigation of risks:</strong></span></p>
<p>Once risks have been prioritized, mitigation strategies need to be developed and implemented to reduce the likelihood or impact of identified risks. This can involve techniques such as risk avoidance, risk transfer, risk reduction, and risk acceptance.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Monitoring of risks:</strong></span></p>
<p>Once mitigation strategies have been implemented, it is important to monitor the effectiveness of these strategies and to track changes in the risk environment over time. This can help identify new risks or changes in the severity of existing risks.</p>
<p>Effective software risk management requires a combination of technical expertise, project management skills, and effective communication and collaboration between stakeholders. By proactively assessing and managing software risk, organizations can improve the quality and reliability of their software, reduce the risk of project failure, and enhance overall business performance.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss the ethical implications of AI.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Artificial Intelligence (AI) is a rapidly developing technology that has the potential to transform many aspects of society, including healthcare, education, transportation, and the workplace. However, AI also raises a number of ethical implications that need to be carefully considered and addressed. Some of the key ethical implications of AI are:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Bias and discrimination:</strong></span></p>
<p>AI systems are only as good as the data they are trained on, and if that data is biased or discriminatory, the AI system can perpetuate and even amplify that bias. For example, facial recognition technology has been shown to be less accurate when identifying people with darker skin tones, which can lead to discrimination and injustice.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Privacy and security:</strong></span></p>
<p>AI systems often require large amounts of data to be collected and analyzed, which can pose risks to privacy and security. There is also the risk that AI systems could be hacked or manipulated, leading to data breaches or other forms of cybercrime.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Responsibility and accountability:</strong></span></p>
<p>AI systems can make decisions that have significant impacts on people&#8217;s lives, but it can be difficult to determine who is responsible when something goes wrong. There are also questions about who should be held accountable for the actions of an AI system, especially when it operates autonomously.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Job displacement:</strong></span></p>
<p>As AI systems become more advanced, there is a risk that they will displace human workers, leading to job losses and economic disruption. This raises important ethical questions about how to ensure that the benefits of AI are shared fairly across society.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Autonomy and control:</strong></span></p>
<p>As AI systems become more advanced, there is a risk that they will become increasingly autonomous and difficult to control. This raises important ethical questions about who should have the power to make decisions about the use and development of AI, and how to ensure that AI systems are developed and used in ways that align with human values and ethics.</p>
<p>Overall, the ethical implications of AI are complex and multifaceted and require careful consideration and regulation to ensure that AI is developed and used in ways that benefit society as a whole. It is important that policymakers, industry leaders, and researchers work together to develop ethical frameworks and guidelines that promote the responsible and ethical development and use of AI.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss with example storage virtualization and application virtualization.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Storage virtualization and application virtualization are two common types of virtualization used in information technology.</p>
<p>Storage virtualization involves creating a layer of abstraction between physical storage devices and the applications that use them. This allows multiple physical storage devices to be combined into a single virtual storage pool that can be allocated and managed more efficiently. One example of storage virtualization is software-defined storage (SDS), which enables storage resources to be pooled and managed through software, rather than relying on proprietary hardware. SDS can be used to create a highly scalable and flexible storage infrastructure that can be easily adapted to changing business needs.</p>
<p>Application virtualization, on the other hand, involves isolating an application from the underlying operating system and hardware, allowing it to run in a self-contained environment. This enables applications to be run on different operating systems or hardware platforms without the need for modification, and also makes it easier to manage and deploy applications across a large number of devices. One example of application virtualization is Microsoft App-V, which enables Windows applications to be delivered and run on client devices without being installed on the local operating system. This can help to reduce the time and cost associated with application management, while also improving security and reducing the risk of conflicts between different applications.</p>
<p>Overall, both storage virtualization and application virtualization offer significant benefits in terms of efficiency, scalability, and flexibility, and are widely used in modern IT environments.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on:</p>
<ol>
<li>Indicators of development</li>
<li>Cyberspace</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Indicators of development:</strong></span><br />
Indicators of development are measures that are used to assess the level of development of a country or region. Some common indicators of development include:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Gross Domestic Product (GDP):</strong> This measures the total economic output of a country or region, including goods and services.</li>
<li><strong>Human Development Index (HDI):</strong> This measures a country&#8217;s level of development based on factors such as education, health, and standard of living.</li>
<li><strong>Poverty rate:</strong> This measures the percentage of the population living below the poverty line.</li>
<li><strong>Life expectancy:</strong> This measures the average lifespan of individuals in a country or region.</li>
<li><strong>Literacy rate:</strong> This measures the percentage of the population that can read and write.</li>
<li><strong>Infant mortality rate:</strong> This measures the number of deaths of infants under the age of one per 1,000 live births.</li>
<li><strong>Gender equality:</strong> This measures the level of equality between men and women in areas such as education, employment, and political participation.</li>
</ol>
<p>These indicators can be used to compare the level of development between different countries or regions, and to track changes in development over time. However, it is important to note that these indicators are not always perfect measures of development and may have limitations in certain contexts.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Cyberspace:</strong></span></p>
<p>Cyberspace refers to the virtual environment created by computer networks, in which people can communicate, share information, and engage in online activities. It is a global network of interconnected computer systems and digital devices, and encompasses a wide range of online platforms, including social media, email, messaging apps, online gaming, and e-commerce websites. Cyberspace is constantly evolving and expanding, and has become an integral part of modern life, transforming the way people communicate, work, learn, and socialize. However, the use of cyberspace also raises important ethical, legal, and security issues, such as privacy, data protection, cybercrime, and online harassment, which require careful consideration and regulation.</p>
</div>
